[1]
Date: Wed 12 Feb 2003
From: Jack Soo <jack.soo@kyip.net>
Source: http://cn.news.yahoo.com/030211/165/1ggup.html [translated by
K. Yip Assoc., edited]
According to the expert [Guangzhou City's Director of the Municipal
Health Bureau, Huang Jiong Lie] the atypical pneumonia is caused by
_Mycoplasma pneumoniae_, which is a small microorganism lying
between the categories of bacteria and [viruses]. [It] causes acute
sickness. Its main symptom is fever,
accompanied by dry cough, less phlegm, and an [acute] respiratory
tract condition.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[_Mycoplasma pneumoniae_ is a bacterium that infects the lower
respiratory tract. The disease is asymptomatic or very mild in
children under 5 years old; symptomatic cases are most common among
school-aged children and young adults. Fatalities are rare.
Treatment of Mycoplasma infections is with erythromycin, other
macrolides, or tetracyclines. A large outbreak with many hospitalized
patients, particularly health care workers, would be unusual.
Mycoplasma infections have a long incubation period, typically 2-3
weeks, compared to the short incubation periods of most respiratory
viruses. It would be interesting to know the suspected incubation
period in this outbreak. In the absence of details as to how this
diagnosis of Mycoplasma was made, and the lack of subsequent
confirmatory reports (see [4] below), this diagnosis must be
considered quite speculative. ProMED-mail awaits further details. -
Mods.JW&LM]
