[2]
Date: Wed 12 Feb 2003 07:18:20 -0800 (PST)
From: Marianne Hopp <mjhopp12@yahoo.com>
Source: WHO Disease Outbreak Reported 12 Feb 2003 [edited]
<http://www.who.int/csr/don/2003_02_12a/en/>

Health officials from Guangdong Province have reported a total of 305
cases and 5 deaths of acute respiratory syndrome from 16 Nov 2002 - 9
Feb 2003 (see previous report:
<http://www.who.int/csr/don/2003_02_11/en/>)
A team from the Chinese Ministry of Health is working with Guangdong
health officials to investigate the outbreak and collect samples for
laboratory analysis. To date, virus isolation for influenza has been
negative.
Cases have been reported from 6 municipalities in Guangdong Province:
Foshan, Guangzhou, Heyuan, Jiangmen, Shenzhen, and Zhongshan. No new
cases have been reported in Foshan, Heyuan, or Zhongshan during the
past week. The number of new cases is decreasing in Guangzhou,
Jiangmen, and Shenzhen municipalities.
******
[3]
Date: Wed, 12 Feb 2003 08:38:35 +0100
From: Johannes Most <jm@mb-lab.com>
Source: China Daily 12 Feb 2003 [edited]

Pneumonia outbreak in Guangdong under control
--------------------------------------------------
Huang Qingdao, director of the Guangdong Provincial Health Bureau,
said 305 people had been found to have contracted the disease between
16 Nov 2002 and 9 Feb 2003. 5 patients have died, including a
10-year-old boy, a 36-year-old teacher, and 3 men aged between 45 and
56 years. The patients include 105 doctors, nurses, and other medical
workers who were apparently infected by the disease while treating
the victims. [The age range and spread to health workers fits the
profile of mycoplasma infection commented upon above. - Mod.JW]
Huang said the patients were found in 6 cities -- Guangzhou,
Shenzhen, Zhongshan, Jiangmen, Foshan, and Heyuan -- in the province
bordering Hong Kong and Macao. A total of 226 pneumonia patients,
including 2 deaths, were detected in Guangzhou, capital of Guangdong
Province, which has more than 80 million people.
Huang told the press Tuesday there had been no new pneumonia cases
reported in Heyuan, Zhongshan, or Foshan in the past week. The number
of new patients decreased in Guangzhou, Shenzhen, and Jiangmen, Huang
added. He said 59 patients had recovered and left hospital and that
those still hospitalized are in stable condition.
--
Johannes Most, MD
<jm@mb-lab.com>
